AB  - Research has documented some of the deleterious effects of discrimination and racism on Asian Americans' psychological and physical health. Using the National Latino and Asian American dataset, we proposed and tested a mediation model of the effects of discrimination on psychological and physical health for Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders. Due to the variations in racial and ethnic classification of many Asian ethnic groups, we tested this model for three Asian ethnic groups. It was hypothesized that psychological distress would mediate the relationship between discrimination and physical health for Chinese, Pilipino, and Vietnamese Americans. The results indicated that psychological distress mediated the effects of discrimination on self-reported physical health for all three Asian ethnic groups; however, the magnitude of these relationships differed for each ethnic group based on the results of multigroup comparison analyses. The implications of results are discussed in relation to understanding Asian American health and within-group variability in the AAPI community.
